(1635, 1, 'W. Amsler Equipment Inc.', 'sales@amslerequipment.net', '1-1245 Re id St, RICHMOND HILL, Ontario, Canada', 'www.amslerequipment.net ', '(905) 707-6704', '(905) 707-6707', '', '<p>&nbsp;Since 1994 W Amsler Equipment Inc. has been designing and building &nbsp;all-electric PET stretch blow molders, empty bottle leak testers and spin dome trimmers in Ontario, Canada. &nbsp;Amsler\'s machines are designed by Werner Amsler, who, for many years, owned and operated his own extrusion blow molding company and who knows what is important to the operators who run and maintain machines in production. &nbsp;Amsler prides itself on its ease of communication about any subject from the design of a bottle to the best choice of equipment to how to solve a problem at a customer\'s factory.</p>\r\n<div>Amsler&rsquo;s complete line of equipment includes all electric PET stretch blow molding machinery and ancillaries such as compressors, chillers, conveyors, bottle inspection units, and filling lines. We also provide a range of services, including pilot production runs, bottle design and development. &nbsp;Through Amsler Packaging Technology we offer rotary liquid filling lines, conveyors, cappers, &nbsp;labelers, turnkey plant design and set up.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Amsler is your best source for bottle design, preform sourcing, molds, PET blow molders, leak detectors, gaylord dumpers and trimmers as well as for all of the auxiliary equipment that goes into bottle production. &nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>At Amsler\'s factory, several machines are always available for bottle development, mold testing, or pilot production runs to meet urgent deliveries.&nbsp;</div>', ''),
(1636, 1, 'W. Sears Seafoods Ltd.', 'wsearsseafoods@eastlink.ca', 'PO Box 9, CLARKS HARBOUR, Nova Scotia, Canada ', '', '(902) 745-2761', '(902) 745-0917', '', '<p>&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12.8000001907349px;\">Seafood Product Preparation &amp; Packaging &nbsp;</span></p>', ''),
(1637, 1, 'W.A. Electric Controls Ltd.', 'waec@waelectric.ca', '10-280 Perry St., PETERBOROUGH,, Ontario, Canada', 'www.waelectric.ca ', '(705) 742-2688', '(705) 742-1514', '', '<p>&nbsp;In 1985, WAEC purchased the design and manufacturing rights for the CR7092C and CR2000 motor control centers from Canadian General Electric (CGE). We continue to manufacture and supply renewal parts, plug-in-units and complete add-on or stand alone sections for MCCs installed by CGE prior to and by WAEC since 1985.</p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>The People</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>All of the engineering and production employees at WAEC previously worked for CGE designing and building motor control centers. As such, no one in the electrical industry knows more about the CR7092C and CR2000 MCC&rsquo;s than the staff at WAEC.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>The Products</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Simply put &ndash; Factory Original</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Since we purchased the complete motor control center business from CGE we are pleased to inform you that all products produced by WAEC are equivalent to factory original. There is no guess work involved. Each part conforms to original factory specifications and will install quickly and easily into the equipment.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Replacement units &amp; parts for the CR7092C and CR2000 employ modern starters, disconnects, and breakers. Every MCC unit is custom-built to satisfy your specifications. Our MCC\'s are very cost effective and we provide quick service when you need to upgrade.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>WAEC also manufactures the CR9440 magnetector line of proximity switches. &nbsp;These magnetic switches are ideal for those locations either too harsh or dirty for normal sensors. &nbsp;The CR9440 sensor can sense distances of .5&quot; to 5&quot;. &nbsp;These sensors are CSA approved for Class 1 Groups C&amp;D and Class II Groups F&amp;G hazardous locations.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>WAEC is the AUTHORIZED DISTRIBUTOR for GE Industrial Systems/Electrical Distribution and Control Products for eastern Ontario. Our distribution products include standard motor control products (push buttons, pilot devices, switches, starters, etc.), circuit breakers, panel boards, busway and transformers.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>WAEC provides excellent customer service and short manufacturing lead time for all our products.</div>', ''),
(1638, 1, 'W.N. Seafoods Unlimited', 'waden@eastlink.ca', '598 Hwy. 304 , Overton, Nova Scotia, Canada', 'www.yarmouthbar.com ', '(902) 742-2461', '(902) 742-0229', '', '<p>&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12.8000001907349px;\">Seafood Product Preparation and Packaging</span></p>', ''),
(1639, 1, 'W.T. Lynch Foods Limited', 'slynch@lynchfoods.com', '72 Railside Rd, NORTH YORK, Ontario, Canada ', 'www.lynchfoods.com ', '(416) 449-5464', '(416) 449-9165', '', '<p>&nbsp;Founded in 1942 by Walker T. Lynch, as a custom manufacturer of syrups and fruit based products for the Foodservice and Dairy Industries, W.T. Lynch Foods Limited has grown steadily to become one of the biggest independently owned food manufacturing companies in Canada.</p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Today, Lynch Foods manufacturers over 1,000 items for the Foodservice and Consumer Goods Industries under both Lynch Corporate labels and Custom private labels.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Many consumers enjoy the Great Taste of Lynch manufactured grocery products, including: Dessert Toppings, Chocolate Syrup, Corn Syrup, Mincemeat, Condiment sauces, Asian sauces, Marinades as well as Hot Drink and Iced Tea mixes.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Lynch Foods\' best-known product lines to the Foodservice Industry are: Ice Cream and Dessert Toppings, Jelly and Dessert Powders, Fruit Toppings and Pie Fillings, Jams and Jellies, Hot Chocolates, Hot Apple Cider Mixes, Iced Tea and Drink mixes, Soup and Gravy products and Sauces.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Lynch prides itself on its superior product quality, industry-leading order fill rates, quality control standards and its research and development.</div>', ''),
(1640, 1, 'Wabi Iron & Steel Corp.', 'sales@wabicorp.com', '330 Broadwood Ave, NEW LISKEARD, Ontario, Canada ', 'www.wabicorp.com ', '(705) 647-4383', '(705) 647-6954', '', '<p>&nbsp;Founded in 1907, Wabi Iron &amp; Steel Corp. has evolved into a leading manufacturer of loading and conveyance systems for the mining industry and one of North America&rsquo;s premier producers of general and abrasion-resistant castings in iron and steel. Innovation drives us to satisfy customer needs whether it&rsquo;s developing high-volume haulage equipment such as mine ore cars and skips or producing customized wear resistant castings for crushers. All of our superior products are carefully manufactured on site, ensuring consistent performance.</p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Wabi has two divisions, each responsible for crafting precision equipment and products for specific purposes. With our head office, fabrication facility, machine shop and foundry located in New Liskeard, Ontario, we maintain control over the entire manufacturing process and ensure quality workmanship on each and every project. Our products are shipped to clients in Canada and the United States as well as Mexico and South America.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Wabi Iron &amp; Steel&rsquo;s Mine Equipment Division fabricates, machines and assembles a wide range of equipment in both steel and aluminum including mine skips, underground rail cars and mine cages. Our manufacturing experience and outstanding engineering capabilities are evident in every product we produce whether it&rsquo;s a 174-man double-deck cage, a 50-tonne skip for a potash mine or Granby-style mine rail cars. Wabi&rsquo;s skilled engineers can design and develop practical solutions to satisfy unique operating requirements. We take pride in working in close partnership with our customers to understand and satisfy their specific production needs and to take care of all of their after-sales service requirements. Wabi also offers an on-site Conveyance Inspection Service to ensure that a customer&rsquo;s equipment meets the stringent demands of mining. Our experts can assess shaft conveyance systems and determine whether or not they need maintenance or re-certification.</div>', ''),
(1641, 1, 'Wajax Industrial Components', 'dfritz@wajax.com', 'Annacis Business Park 746 Chester Rd, DELTA, British Columbia, Canada', 'www.kamandirect.com ', '(604) 523-2356', '(604) 523-2366', '', '<p style=\"margin-top: 0em; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 16.7999992370605px;\">Kaman Industrial Technologies is a subsidiary of&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.kaman.com/\" target=\"_blank\" style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">Kaman Corporation</a>, a diversified $1 billion company providing high technology products and services.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 16.7999992370605px;\">With nearly 200 branches and major regional distribution centers and over 35 years in the business, we are one of North America\'s largest industrial distributors. We provide a wide range of products and systems related to bearings, mechanical and electrical power transmission, automation &amp; control, material handling, and fluid power for the MRO and OEM markets.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 16.7999992370605px;\">Kaman Industrial Technologies brings our commitment of technological leadership and value-added services to the Industrial Distribution business. While our core business lies in the supply and application of standard components, we also offer customers single-source responsibility and accountability for each product line.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 16.7999992370605px;\">We offer programs that go beyond the role of product provider; programs proven to deliver a reduction in the total cost of doing business. With the same spirit of innovation that drove Charles Kaman to found Kaman Corporation 50 years ago, our people are thinkers, problem solvers, engineers, and solution providers.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 16.7999992370605px;\">Our focus on customer service is facilitated both by this dedication to innovation, as well as our hands-on local presence. A Professional Account Manager has direct responsibility for each individual plant location we service. The primary contact on a day-to-day basis, this person works closely with branch operating staff to handle the daily requirements. This relationship between customer and branch is the grass roots of our day-to-day business, and is supported by sales and operational management teams within our organization. The core of our business, our local facilities are backed by national resources.</p>\r\n<p style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 16.7999992370605px;\">A dedication to ingenuity is only as deliverable as the capability of the people involved. To this end, we seek out and employ product specialists throughout the company with established expertise in the areas of automation &amp; control, mechanical, electrical, fluid power, and material handling. Specialists provide our customers specific product expertise in trouble-shooting, upgrading from a current product, and securing cost-effective alternatives.</p>', ''),
(1642, 1, 'Wbs Distribution', 'ventes@bofflitsescamotables.com', '805, rue Galt O, SHERBROOKE, Quebec, Canada', 'www.wbsdistribution.com ', '(819) 565-0433', '(819) 565-5619', '', '<p>&nbsp;Our mechanisms are delivered throughout the world via UPS along with a complete layout for the manufacture and assembly of your retractable bed. If you are a dealer, please feel free to contact us !</p>', ''),
(1643, 1, 'WCC CRANE SOLUTIONS INC', 'rano@shaw.ca', '1202-212 Davie St, VANCOUVER, British Columbia, Canada', 'WCCCRANESOLUTIONS.COM ', '(604) 780-2321', '(604) 261-4025', '', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\">WCC Crane Solutions Inc. was established in 2003 in Vancouver, British Columbia.<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\">The mission of WCC Crane Solutions Inc. is to provide clients across British Columbia with engineering consulting services of all types of overhead cranes; from concept planning through to completion, with highly professional expertise using common sense and practical experience.<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\">In the last eight years, WCC Crane Solutions has serviced over 1000 projects ranging from $1K to $100K in consulting fees for the design of special application uses for cranes and hoists. Clients have included manufacturing industries, mines and sawmills throughout British Columbia, Alberta, Manitoba and Alaska, Washington States, and Oregon.<o:p></o:p></p>', ''),
(1644, 1, 'WCP Inc.', 'info@wcpconsulting.com', '201 Franklin Ave, THORNHILL, Ontario, Canada', 'www.wcpconsulting.com ', '(905) 660-7184', '(877) 224-9867', '', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\">At World Class Productivity (WCP), we help individuals and organizations improve their productivity in managing projects. Improved project productivity results in more efficient use of resources, less overtime, fewer cost overruns, fewer complaints, more satisfied clients, and greater profits. To help our clients, we provide a full range of project management training and consulting services that have helped leading companies and organizations in Canada and the United States since 1995.<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\">Our highly interactive courses incorporate the best in adult learning principles to provide participants with hands-on project management tools and practical skills they can apply as soon as they leave the course. Our services are geared to organizations and individuals serious about improving their organization&rsquo;s project management effectiveness and maturity.<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\">Our 3-day fundamental level Project Management Essentials (PME) course is likely one of the most popular and longest running&nbsp; project management courses in Canada, with over 8000 participants estimated to have taken the course since it was first introduced over 15 years ago. Courses like our 2-day Hands-on Microsoft Project (MSP) course and our 2-dayJuggling Multiple Projects course (the first of its kind in Canada) are the standard by which other similar courses are measured.<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\">WCP courses are available for in-house delivery anywhere in Canada and the United States, and have been delivered to over 100 in-house clients representing over a dozen industry sectors including government, healthcare, banking, insurance, IT, mining, utilities, telecommunication, construction and manufacturing. Our most popular project management courses are offered publicly in association with the University of Toronto and the University of Waterloo, and are part of both basic and advanced Project management Certificate programs. It is not surprising that World Class Productivity has established itself as a leading PM training and consulting provider among the Canadian project management community.<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\">Whether preparing your team for an important project, or upgrading your skills to become a Project Management Professional (PMP&reg;) &mdash; if you are serious about applying project management, you came to the right place.<o:p></o:p></p>', ''),
(1645, 1, 'we c.a.r.e.', 'eggertson@renewables.ca', '7885 Jocktrail Rd, RICHMOND, Ontario, Canada ', '/www.renewables.ca ', '(613) 222-6920', '(613) 822-4987', '', '<p>&nbsp;2014-10-21 (canadian association for renewable energies) There are &ldquo;many potential supply mixes&rdquo; to facilitate wind energy in Canada and &ldquo;the vast majority of them are much less greenhouse gas intensive&rdquo; than described in a study commissioned by the nuclear industry. The literature review of lifecycle assessment of wind, nuclear and natural gas generation claims that emissions from wind and nuclear are similar, with the exception of GHG emissions where wind produces &ldquo;distinctly less&rdquo; emissions than nuclear. The nuclear study claims that nuclear can be less GHG intensive than a scenario where wind and natural gas jointly generate power. The Canadian Wind Energy Association says wind can partner with hydroelectric, solar or energy storage and DSM technologies and, &ldquo;by choosing to focus on only one scenario, the study failed to consider a broad range of equally or more plausible scenarios for the future evolution of Canada\'s electricity grid.&rdquo; GHG emissions must be &ldquo;an increasingly important consideration in the selection of future sources&rdquo; of electricity, but CanWEA adds that the cost-competitiveness of new generation sources and their overall environmental performance and economic benefits are also important. Wind is cheaper than new nuclear reactors and is cost-competitive with new hydroelectric facilities, and is not subject to commodity and carbon price risks facing natural gas.</p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>2014-10-21 (canadian association for renewable energies) The 140 MW solar PV facility in Kingston was one of the top asset finance transactions of the third quarter of this year, at $525 million, according the latest &lsquo;Global Trends in Clean Energy Investment&rsquo; produced by Bloomberg New Energy Finance. Total investment in Canada was $1.9 billion in Q3, up from $1.3 bn in Q2, and compares with $7.3 bn in the US, down from $10.7 bn in Q2 but up from $5.7 bn in Q3 of last year. Global investment in renewables totalled $175 bn in the first three quarters of 2014 &ldquo;as the sector shows signs of a worldwide recovery after a two-year slump,&rdquo; with most of the increase in China and Japan. Support fell to an eight-year low in Europe. &ldquo;There is no room for complacency because clean energy investment of between $200 bn and $300 bn a year is not large enough to herald the rapid transformation of the power system that experts say is required if the world is to see a peak in CO2 emissions around 2020,&rdquo; the report notes.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>', ''),
(1646, 1, 'Wearable Art Designer Jewellery', 'ljewell752@gmail.com', '752 Gillespie Ave, PETERBOROUGH, Ontario, Canada', '', '(705) 748-3061', '', '', '<p>&nbsp;Gold, silver and gemstone jewellery, custom ordered by the choice of stones and chain styles. All designs are original and hand made</p>', ''),
(1647, 1, 'WG McKay Limited', 'info@wgmckay.com', '100-40 University Ave, TORONTO, Ontario, Canada', 'www.wgmckay.com ', '(416) 510-1040', '(416) 510-8422', '', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\">As one of Canada\'s oldest and most respected customs brokerage firms, W. G. McKay Limited has consistently maintained the personal service that has made us successful for 100 years.<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\">Our approach is simple: provide a quality service without sacrificing value. This objective is achieved on a daily basis by combining sophisticated information technology with personalized service utilizing the talents of the 21 Certified Customs Specialists we have on staff.<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\">Based on size we are among the top twenty Customs brokerage firms in a Canadian industry comprised of over 250 companies.<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\">Also known as a Customs House Broker, A CUSTOMS BROKER is a specialized facilitator, skilled in helping clients find the most cost-effective ways to move trade consignments around the world, allowing importers to focus on what they do best, selling their goods.<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\">CUSTOMS Brokers&rsquo; are licensed by the federal government, as are most of the employees of the firm. While in most cases any duly authorized agent may transact business with the CBSA on behalf of clients, only a licensed customs broker may account for goods and pay duties under the Customs Act as an agent of an importer or owner.<o:p></o:p></p>', ''),
(1648, 1, 'WG Wood Sales Company Limited', 'woodsaleswgtracy@bellnet.ca', '17-563 Edward Ave, RICHMOND HILL, Ontario, Canada ', 'www.wgwoodsales.com', '(416) 798-7202', '(905) 508-4963', '', '<p>&nbsp;W.G. Wood Sales Company Limited is a natural industry leader&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div>*W.G. Wood Sales Company Limited specializes in the Supply &amp; Installation of Division 10 Specialties &#150; Lockers, Toilet Stalls and Washroom Accessories&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>*Many custom products are available&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>*Police Lockers are a great fit for all officers&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>*W.G. Wood Sales Company Limited has handled some of the most challenging construction projects in Ontario, Quebec, the United States and Carribean&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>*Unionized installation teams available to help complete even the most time sensitive deadlines&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>*Leed certified materials&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>*W.G. Wood Sales Company Limited deal with all levels of Government, both in Canada and the United States&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>*Fantastic warranties are backed by all manufacturers&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>*W.G. Wood Sales Company Limited\'s expert staff is trained to get you the best possible product for your requirement, no matter the timeline&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>*Police lockers are installed in Army Reserve Facilities, Air Force Bases, Fire Stations, Drug Enforcement Facilities, US Coast Guard and US Army Facilities&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>*We were also a specified supplier for the US Pentagon&nbsp;</div>', ''),
(1649, 1, 'What\'s Up Clothing Co.', 'petey@whatsupcc.com', '123-4056 Meadowbrook Dr., LONDON, Ontario, Canada', 'www.whatsupcc.com ', '(519) 652-6781', '(519) 652-9860', '', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\">Established in 1998, What&rsquo;s Up Clothing Company provides a full line of advertising, marketing and promotional products to meet the needs of your company. We have access to thousands of products from clothing and hats to other hard good such as pens, mugs and tool kits etc.<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\">Our staff is always looking for the best promotional product for the best price for your business, event or sports team or tournament.<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\">We are full of ideas that will fit any budget and have frequent features that you can take advantage of.<o:p></o:p></p>', ''),
(1650, 1, 'White Witch Logistics Inc', 'whitewitch.logistics@gmail.com', '7 Walker Rd E, CALEDON EAST, Ontario, Canada', '', '(416) 931-0693', '(905) 584-5471', '', '<p>&nbsp;Worldwide passenger and cargo charter services. Executive and group air charters. Outsized cargo specialists providing ADHOC and ACMI operations.&nbsp;</p>', ''),
(1651, 1, 'WiBand Communications Corp', 'sales@wiband.com', '187 Commerce Dr., Winnipeg, Manitoba, Canada', 'www.wiband.com ', '(780) 430-4002', '(780) 430-4079', '', '<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\">WiBand Communications Corp. has been providing innovative custom communications solutions to our customers across Western Canada since 1999. Headquartered in Winnipeg, Manitoba, WiBand also has branch offices in Vancouver, Calgary, Edmonton and Regina, servicing over 100 urban and rural centres in British Columbia, Alberta, Manitoba and Saskatchewan.<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\">WiBand Communications uses a combination of fixed wireless, fibre, cable and DSL to provide our customers with fully redundant internet and data solutions. Whether the solution is as simple as a basic commercial internet connection or as complex as the deployment of a multi-site MPLS network, WiBand consistently exceeds customer expectations by delivering reliable high quality solutions.<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"text-align:justify\">WiBand Communications understands the mission critical nature of the service we provide to our clients. From installation timelines to connection up-time, WiBand has a strong sense of urgency and responds to our clients faster than our competitors. We consider our clients partners and deal with them with the highest level of integrity. We build better connections &ndash; with our clients, for our clients.<o:p></o:p></p>', ''),
(1652, 1, 'Wiggers Custom Furniture Ltd.', 'jwiggers@wiggersfurniture.com', 'P.O. Box 518 , BEAVERTON, Ontario, Canada ', 'www.wiggersfurniture.com ', '(705) 426-9141', '(905) 985-0889', '', '<p>&nbsp;We are a small family owned woodworking studio that has been in business since 1967. Our multi-generational tradition of craft is based on doing high quality work with the utmost of attention to detail.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>In addition to wood we also work in a variety of other mediums including glass, metal leaf, parchment, shagreen, stone, stainless steel and mother-of-pearl.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Over the past 46 years we have collaborated with some of the world\'s most renowned designers and furniture collections including J. Wade Beam, Brueton, Dakota Jackson, Vladimir Kagan, Mitchell Pickard, Jill Salisbury, Ron Seff, Shaver/Melahn and Lee Weitzman.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Commissions of our work can be found in private residences and commercial interiors located as far away as Russia, the Middle East and Asia. 5-Star hotels including Four Seasons, Mandarin Oriental, Ritz-Carlton, and The Umstead have also commissioned pieces for their public areas and luxury executive suites.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>For more than 2 decades we have also placed great emphasis on the use of environmentally responsible materials and practices, including reclaimed and FSC certified sustainably harvested wood; NAUF and CARB2 compliant panels, non-UF glues, and low VOC finishes</div>', ''),
(1653, 1, 'WJ Packaging Solutions Corp', 'info@wjpkg.com', '255-13900 Maycrest Way, RICHMOND, British Columbia, Canada', '', '(604) 303-5920', '(604) 303-5922', '', '<p>&nbsp;WJ Packaging Solutions Corp. is the North American branch office of one of the most reputable packaging manufacturer in Korea. As an ISO 9001 certified manufacturer, we have been supplying roto gravure printed packaging materials to over 130 companies worldwide for the past 47 years. WJ Packaging Solutions Corp. utilizes only materials approved by the FDA and its products have been approved by the CFIA for direct food contact since 1999. With our in-house design capabilities, gravure printing, laminating, cold seal application, slitting, pouch making, and spout attachment, WJ Packaging Solutions Corp. has been the one-stop packaging solutions for our customers&rsquo; projects. We enable them to achieve the highest value their packaging can offer.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>As flexible packaging manufacturer, we also offer our packaging machinery for customer who needs not only flexible packaging materials but also machinery for food, pharmaceutics and chemical products such as Vertical Form Fill Seal, Hot Fill, Vacuum Packaging, Stick Pack, and Fill &amp; Seal Packaging Machines. The manufacturer was established in 1952 which is one of the reputable and reliable packaging machinery manufacturers in Korea. Many industrial decision makers have been through its manufacturer and applied its technologies for their foundation of business.&nbsp;</div>', ''),
(1654, 1, 'WJF Instrumentation (1990) Ltd.', 'info@wjf.ca', '5-3610 29 St NE, Calgary, Alberta, Canada', 'www.wjf.ca ', '(403) 291-5570', '(403) 291-3714', '', '<p>&nbsp;WJF Instrumentation, based in Calgary, Alberta, was founded in 1984 to serve the process control and analytical instrumentation needs of Western Canada.</p>\r\n<div>We help our clients with analytical and process control requirements in the industrial and municipal industries. We also provide some instrumentation and service to the laboratory and environmental markets. With inventory</div>\r\n<div>stocked in Calgary, we can provide fast replacements for consumable items,as well as quick solutions for new measurement applications. That, in addition to most of our equipment able to be serviced in our Calgary office,</div>\r\n<div>means fast turn-around and minimal down-time for our clients.</div>', ''),
(1655, 1, 'WLON Distribution Ltd', 'info@wlondistribution.ca', '61 Main St, DRYDEN, Ontario, Canada', 'www.wlondistribution.ca ', '(807) 938-1962', '(807) 938-1964', '', '<p>&nbsp;Wabigoon Lake Ojibway Nation is a First Nation community located in the heart of the Canadian Shield lake country to Northwestern Ontario. The five hundred members of Wabigoon belong to the great Ojibway Nation of the Great Lakes region of Canada and the United States. It extends west from the Great Lakes to Manitoba, Minnesota and beyond. Approximately two hundred members of the First Nation live on the Wabigoon reservation and another two hundred live in the local area and they participate in its economic and cultural life. The formal leadership of the community is through Chief and Council. Chief and Council are determined by vote of community members.</p>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>The ancient presence of Wabigoon Lake Ojibway Nation people on their land is reflected in its vast forests and countless lakes, rivers and streams. This landscape is in turn reflected in them in their language, culture and way of life. Extensive fields of Manomin (wild rice) were planted by the ancestors and now form an abundant source of food for people and animals. Vast towering stands of pine, birch, cedar and spruce, as well as blueberries and other foods, were nurtured by an extensive knowledge and practice of controlled burning. The homeland of Wabigoon people is an Ojibway cultural landscape.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>The members of Wabigoon Lake Ojibway Nation are descendants of signatories of an Indian Treaty with the British Crown in Right of Canada that covers 55,000 square miles of land. Treaty #3 was signed in October of 1873.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Wabigoon Lake Ojibway Nation is rapidly becoming a native community with a vibrant renewed native cultural, social and economic life. Now emerging from a history of extreme hardship and privation, the First Nation has become a progressive force for renewal throughout the Treaty #3 region. The history of Wabigoon people includes the tragedy of demographic collapse that resulted from the ravages of sickness and disease that was brought to Canada by European explorers, missionaries, government officials and settlers. This was followed by systematic cultural suppression including the outlawing of their sacred religious ceremonies by the Government of Canada. This suppression by the Government of Canada was so pervasive that status Indians were not recognized as &quot;persons&quot; under Canadian law until 1960.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Even during their years of privation and hardship, Wabigoon Lake Ojibway Nation people were planting the seeds of their cultural and economic renewal. The Wabigoon Nation held fast to their traditional spirit of survival and enterprise. For example, when a dam was built by the settler forestry industry at Dryden in 1896, extensive fields of Manomin and hay pastures were flooded. Where Manomin fields were flooded the plant could grow no more. In response, Wabigoon people undertook a systematic program of taking Manomin from local lakes unaffected by the flooding and planting it into their hay pastures that were now under shallow water. The Manomin fields there today include some of the most extensive in the region. They are so ecologically as well as economically significant that they are now protected by the Government of Ontario. These Manomin fields support the only native wild rice processing plant in Canada - a facility built by Wabigoon people in 1988 and located on the Wabigoon reservation. In the late 1950\'s and early 1960\'s the Government of Ontario engaged in a systematic effort to develop and implement legislation that would have seen the alienation of most of the tribally held rice fields in the Treaty #3 into non-native hands. It was the Chief of Wabigoon, Chief Paul Pitchenese, who led the successful effort to prevent this from happening. Without this effort a native-owned wild rice processing plant would not exist on the Wabigoon reservation today.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>The pro-active efforts of Wabigoon Lake Ojibway Nation towards economic self-determination have been applied in a variety of areas. Some members of Wabigoon are now fifth generation native Ojibway loggers. Even when an Indian Agent was unlawfully selling timber resources from the Wabigoon reservation a century ago (sales which have now given rise to a lawful land claim that is currently being resolved with the Government of Canada), Wabigoon people were fighting to participate fully in the regional forestry industry. Now the First Nation is home to the most successful native logging enterprise in Ontario. This enterprise is an integrated &quot;stump to dump&quot; operation where an Ojibway company does everything from building forest access roads to delivering wood that it harvests to regional mills. Wabigoon Lake Ojibway Nation has built on this success; it operates a successful tree nursery that now grows six million seedlings under contract with mainstream forestry companies. The community is currently expanding into a value-added forest products tribal enterprise venture.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>The members of Wabigoon Lake Ojibway Nation have developed a progressive culture of tribal economic and cultural entrepreneurship. What is meant by cultural entrepreneurship? It is a pro-active approach to cultural renewal. For more than a century the cultural practices of the Ojibway people were suppressed in Canada. As already noted, their sacred ceremonies were outlawed. It was in the context of this legacy of discrimination that Wabigoon Lake Ojibway Nation became the first community in the Treaty #3 region to hold an open and public &quot;traditional powwow&quot;. This happened in the 1970\'s.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>The economic and cultural renewal that can be readily seen taking place at Wabigoon Lake Ojibway Nation today is, in effect, the culmination of generations of work and preparation. The dividends of this effort are growing. For example, the wild rice processing plant on the Wabigoon', ''),
